<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-615  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 615.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Sept 10 1990 v36 n1826 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dumping ground. (antidumping cases filed with the GeneralAgreement on Tariffs and Trade since 1980) (Government Closeup)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) reports thatsince 1980 the largest number of antidumping cases (384) werefiled against the European Community (EC) by GATT partners,compared with 144 complaints filed against the US and 159 filedagainst Japan.andP;  Australia has launched the largest number ofantidumping complaints (421), compared to 395 for the US, 294 forCanada and 271 for the EC; the four combined accounted for 95percent of all antidumping cases reported since 1980 to GATT.andO;Many Pacific Rim and newly industrialized countries propose asimplified antidumping code that ignores or discounts the highstartup cost of new products when making antidumping costcalculations.andP;  Most US firms want to tighten some antidumpingprocedures, either in the GATT code or in US law; US companiesagree that faster investigations and stiffer penalities for repeatoffenders are needed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeRegulationTrade and Professional AssociationsReportsTrendsGeneral Agreement on Tariffs and TradeSemiconductor industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>